  "title": "Skill: Mathematical Symbols",
  "body": " Skill: Mathematical Symbols   You will encounter many mathematical symbols during your math courses. The table below provides you with a list of the more common symbols, how to read them, and notes on their meaning and usage. The following page has a series of examples of these symbols in use.    Symbol  How to read it  Notes on meaning and usage     equals  and have exactly the same value.    or  is approximately equal to  Do not write when you mean .     implies  If is true, then is also true.     is implied by  If is true, then is also true.     or  iff     is equivalent to or  if and only if    and imply each other.     the point   A coordinate in .     the open interval from to  The values between and , but not including the endpoints.     the closed interval from to  The values between and , including the endpoints.     The (half-open) interval from to excluding , and including .  The values between and , excluding , and including . Similar for .    or  the real numbers  It can also be used for the plane as , and in higher dimensions.    or  the complex numbers  , where .    or  the integers  , , ,0,1,2,3, .    or  the natural numbers  .     is an element of  The variable lies in the set (of values) .     is not an element of      union  The set of all points that fall in or .     intersection  The set of all points that fall in both and .      is a subset of or  is contained in    Any element of is also an element of .     for all  Something is true for all (any) value of (usually with a side condition like ).     there exists  Used in proofs and definitions as a shorthand.     there exists a unique  Used in proofs and definitions as a shorthand.      composed with or  of    Denotes .     factorial  .     the floor of  The nearest integer .     the ceiling of  The nearest integer .    or  is big oh of   . Sometimes the limit is toward or another point.     is little oh of  .     goes to from the right   is approaching , but is always greater than . Similar for .      The Trouble with  The most commonly used, and most commonly misused, symbol is . The symbol means that the things on either side are actually the same, just written a different way. The common misuse of is to mean 'do something'. For example, when asked to compute , some people will write:   .  This claims that , which is false. We can fix this by carrying the along, as in . We could instead use the ' ' symbol, meaning 'implies', and turn it into a logical statement:   .      To Symbol or not to Symbol?    means that , s.t. , .   Although this statement is correct mathematically, it is difficult to read (unless you are well-versed in math-speak). This example shows that although you can write math in all symbols as a shortcut, often it is clearer to use words. A compromise is often preferred.   The Formal Definition of a Limit  Let be defined on an open interval about , except possibly at itself. We say that approaches the limit as approaches , and we write if for every number , there exists a corresponding number such that for all we have .     Other Examples  The symbol should be used even when doing simple algebra.     You will be more comfortable with symbols, and better able to use them, if you connect them with their spoken form and their meaning.   The mathematical notation is read composed with at the point or of of and means .    "
